We used counts of MLH1 foci per cell to estimate the genome wide recombination rates across our panel of 14 wild derived inbred strains sampled from thress subspecies within the house mouse species complex; M. m. domesticus, M. m. musculus. and M. m. molossinus. MLH1 foci were quantified from a total of 1867 spermatocytes and 1409 oocytes. The sampling of prophase oocytes is diffecult and was the limiting factor thus there are some strains with only MLH1 counts from spermatocytes, which are included for sex specific analysises.

Intial examinations of the sex specific data revealed that greater variety in across the strain means in males compared to females. In females, domesticusG, musculusMSM, and domesticuLEW had the greatest differences in means compared to other strains, 1.11, 1.05, and 1.1 respectively. While in the male data the strain average for musculusPWD , molossinusMSM and musculusSKIVE are 1.21, 1.28, and 1.11 higher than the other strain means.

The musculus and molossinus subspecies have a much larger amount of variance across means with the range in mouse means being 21.87 to 31.63 in Musc and 23.18 to 32.19 and Molossinus.

While in two of the subspecies, the means for males show a greater range across means, notable in the molossinus strains 30.37, 23.42 for molossinusMSM and molossinusMOLF respectively. In the musculus the strain means are 28.67, 26.08, 22.99, 23.7, 24.41, 22.31 for musculusPWD, musculusSKIVE, musculusKAZ, musculusTOM, musculusAST, and musculusCZECH respectively. In the male Dom strains the means for MLH1 count per cell are 23.38, 23.16, 24.16, 21.81 for domesticusWSB, domesticusG, domesticusLEW and domesticusPERC respectively.

Evolutionary Framework

In order to test the effects of subspecies, sex and strain on the mean of MLH1 counts per cell, we fit 137 mouse averages of MLH1 foci per cell to a series of mixed and linear models.

M1.Mixed Model \[mouse \ av.\ MLH1\ foci\ per\ cell ~=~ subsp * sex + rand(strain) + \varepsilon \]

Our model, M1., was designed to test the effects of the subspecies, sex, their interaction, and strain as a random effect on the mouse means.

All of the effects within the mixed model were significant (LRT: subsp p= 0, sex p = 6.1810^{-4}, subspecies * sex p = 2.0410^{-4}) and random LTR; strain p= 0).

M2. Linear Model \[mouse \ av.\ MLH1\ foci\ per\ cell ~=~ subsp * sex * strain + \varepsilon\]

M3. LInear Model \[mouse \ av.\ MLH1\ foci\ per\ cell ~=~ sex * strain + \varepsilon\]

Following up with linear models which tested for (subsecies M2), and strain effects alone (M3) both showed similar results so we just report those from M3. also just report effects which were consisantly significant across both M2 and M3

which identified several signifcant sex by strain interaction effects, ( musculusPWDmale and musculusMSMmale ) (glm; p = 5.3510^{-4} and p = 0 )

These results confirm the qualitative observation that within these two strains there has been sex-specific evolution in the average MLH1 count per cell.

Additionally, domesticusG had significant strain and sex by strain effects (p =1.9510^{-6} and 0 for strain and strain by sex effect). These results confirm the qualtative pattern of the domesticusG strain having the largest degree of sexual dimorphism (heterochiasmy) in the dataset.

domesticusG had significant strain (p= 2.37) and sex by strain effects (p =0

A similar glm models (M4) was run on the sex specific data set, (just containing subspecies, strain and the interaction).

M4. \[sex\ specific\ mouse \ av.\ MLH1\ foci\ per\ cell ~=~ subspecies * strain + \varepsilon\]

For the male specific data, three of the strain effects of 13 strains had significant effects on mean MLH1 per cell, PWD (p=7.3710^{-10}), SKIVE (p=0.01) and MSM (p=2.2310^{-14} ). (with effect sizes ranging from 5, 7, and 2 foci respectively). Given these results, theses strains are classified as high rec strains and point to rapid evolution in the recombiantion rate for spermatocytes.

While the female specific linear model has many more had significant strain effects; domesticusG (p=2.510^{-6}), domesticusLEW (p=0.01), domesticusPWD (p=0.02), domesticusMSM(p=6.2410^{-6}), domesticusMOLF(p=0.08), and domesticusKAZ(p=0.1) the effect sizes have a smaller range of four to one, indicateing specific, but small strain effects for the mean number of MLH1 foci per cell.

Within Mouse Variance in CO Count per Cell

In order to more fully discribe the MLH1 count per cell distributions we examined the variance applying the same mixed models and linear models, using the within mouse variance of MLH1 counts per cell as the dependant variable (Table 1).

Within animal variance in CO count / genome wide RR is important because it could shape constraints (and determine how effective stabilizing selection can act (ref))

Following the same basic framework we used for analyzing mean number of MLH1 foci per cell, we applied a set of mixed and linear models to test effects (sex differences for the within mouse variance in MLH1 foci per cell).

M5. Mixed Model \[mouse\ variance\ in \ CO \ per cell ~=~ subsp * sex + rand(strain) + \varepsilon \]

M6. Linear Model \[mouse\ variance\ in \ CO \ per cell ~=~ subsp * sex * strain + \varepsilon\]

M7. Linear Model \[mouse\ variance\ in \ CO \ per cell ~=~ sex * strain + \varepsilon\]

For both the mixed and linear models, sex was the only significant effect (LRT; p= 0, glm; p= 2.310^{-4} mixed and glm models respectively). Since the measures for within mouse variance may be more susceptible to technical error effects from the staining protocol (i.e.background noise). For this reasons, we replicated the model analysis using a subset of cells with higher quality scores. These models replicated the results of the full data set with sex being the most significant effect (LTR; p = 0, and glm; p = 2.310^{-4} ). Sex specific effect linear models indicate that there is no significant difference in the amount of within mouse variance in males. While in females, one strain, domesticusLEW has significantly higher within mouse variance (glm; p = 0) for the model with the full dataset. While in the model using the high quality cells, PWD has the only signicant strain effect (glm; p =0.04) suggesting a lack of a consistant signal for differences in the amount of within mouse variance in oocytes. For the estimates of variance, the replicates are at the level of mouse, unlike MLH1 counts, in which the replicates are at the level of the cell. This limits the power for detecting significance differences across groups,

In an attempt to locatize the above male specific crossover number evolution within the meiotic pathway we quantified a marker for DSBs, DMC1, in early prophase spermtaocytes. DMC1 foci were scored from a total of 76 leptotene and 75 zygotene staged spermatocytes form juvenille mice (12 to 18 days). A subset of strains were choosen to test for differences between the high and low recombination groups; musculusPWD, molossinusMSM, musculusKAZ , domesticusWSB , and domesticusG. One mouse was sampled for each strain.

For all strains there were significantly more foci from leptotene cells compared to zygotene (t.test; p = ), which reflects the expected patterns across the timing of meiosis.

Confirming the prediction that (more crossovers are associated with more initial DSBs), the two high recombining strains tested have significantly more DMC1 foci compared to low recombining strains in leptoene cells (t.test; p=0 , one-way-anova; p=0.00027).

The differences in DMC1 foci were not significant for zygotene cells between the two groups (t.test; p=0.66, one-way-anova; p=0.15).

The ratios of average number of MLH1 and DMC1 foci per cell have . biological significance

The ratios, calculated for DMC1 means from both stages of prophase, are not significantly differet between the strain groups (t.test; p = 0.94 and p=0.11 for leptotene and zygotene based ratios respectively).

These results indicate that the changes which lead to differences in crossover numbers may be established before DSB formation (cite Baier et al 2014).

Chromosome Class Proportions

In order to decompose the cell wide rate, we decided to look at the proportion of chromosome classes (ie by the number crossovers on the same bivalent). A total of 34982 single bivalents were pooled to calculate the average propotion for each chromosome class (Table X).

The first attern we notice from looking at theis large number of samples is that The vast majority of all bivalents in house mouse have one or two crossoverrs (1CO an 2CO), even across sexes.

The general pattern is that most of the chromosom classes are from 1CO (0.69) and 2CO (0.27). This relpicates what has been notice in the literature (cite stapley).

Most of the bivalents are 1CO and 2CO class bivalents and the proportion of these two classes distinguish high and low rec male strains. (distinguish the high rec males from minimal rec groups)

(A previously reported for house mouse, the most prevelent class of chromosomes is the 1CO class. The high rec group of males are the exception indicating, which fits with the conclusion that higher cell wide CO counts are due to more chromosomes(bivalents) have 2 instead of 1 CO. (much smaller proportions and variation in the fringe classes

2. most of the male proportions are 2/3s 1CO and 1/3 2COs. but The high rec strains are distinguishable by having more 2COs at the cost of 1COs, with closer to 1:1

MSM 60% PWD 50% SKIVE 30% 20 - 10% remaining (low) strains

PWD and MSM have slightly different proportions of 1CO and 2CO, (with MSM having more 2COs) (chi-square test; 1CO p =0.04 and 2CO p = 0.06 ).

While the proportions are significantly different, PWD male and MSM male proportions are more similar to each other than strains from the same subspcies (PWD and KAZ chi-square test; 1CO p =4.6210^{-26}, 2CO p=3.1510^{-33}) and MSM and MOLF chi-square test; 1CO p = 2.9510^{-12}, 2CO p=4.7210^{-13}).

3. these results confirm the intuitive conclusion/result that the rapid male specific evolution in gwRR proceeds though the chromosome level/though increasing the number of 2CO bivalents at the expense of 1CO bivalents

Breif conclusion: the evolution of genome wide recombiantion rates proceeds through the chromosome level.

Single Bivalent Level Results

In order to better deconstruct the genome wide recombiation rate, we decided to deconstruct cell wide average by examining features of the recombiantion landscape at the single bivalent level. recombination landscape refers to the i) total length of the SC-AE (potential area for COs), ii) the position of single crossovers along bivalents and iii) the spacing between multiple COs on the same bivalent.

From our total set of cell images 83975 chromosome objects were isolated by the image analysis software. After the human curation step, 10458 single bivalent measures were left. (make sure these are the hand.foci bivalents).

Table X illustrates the break down of single bivalent observations by category. Error compared to human measures and other details have been discribed in (Peterson_2019).

The ranges of of rates of isolating chromosomes per cell are 0.51 in MSM male to 0.72 ) KAZ female, we assume that the isolation process is not biased. Because there are hundreds of observations per category, we assume that each of the 19 autosomes (chromosomes) is equally represented in the dataset of single bivalents. We assume the bivalent datasets across all categories are equally eqivilent for representing general patterns.

We approach two main questions using this single bivalent data set, 1) Which traits are sexually dimorphic? and 2) which traits fit distinsutinguish the high and low recombining strains for males?

Q1. 1CO Position Sex Differences

We focus on the foci positions from one crossover (1CO n= ) bivalents since the landscape patterns for multi crossover bivalents will be highly influences by crossover interference.

We anchor the position measures at the centromere (and normalize by deviding the position by the length of the chromosome, so the value range from 0 to 1, with smaller values representing positions closer to the centromere end of the bivalent, and larger values meaning foci positions closer to the opposite end (refered here as terminal or telomeric position).

We plot the mouse averages across all of the single bivalent measures, with the strain averages shown as boxplots

in order to get a better picture of the sex differences in this foci-position metric

In the domesticus strains the mouse averages for normalized single foci positions were significantly sexually dimorphic (fitting the predictions/pattern of the typical recombination landscape (Sardell)). The single CO positions are medially placed in females and terminall placed in males.

The pavlues across the strains are; (t.test; p = 4.0610^{-4}, 1.6710^{-5}, and 6.9110^{-5} for WSB, G and LEW respectively).

With the musculus and molossinus strains displaying a similar pattern (t.test p = 9.2710^{-5} and 0.04) PWD and MSM. Two musculus strains had a weaker signal, but it was still in the same direction (t.test; p = 0.01, and 0 for KAZ and SKIVE respectively).

motivation: the positive correlation, Our prediction for this metric is that the high rec strain will have longer sc lengths (axis lengths)

The predicted pattern for SC length becomes more nuanced when the data are split up by Chromosome class. Mainly that 1CO are shorter in the high rec strains then low rec strains. Note on Heterochiasmy Definition

I present heterochiasmy as a comparison of oocyte to spermatocyte MLH1 counts, but the sex chromosomes/bivalents complicate this comparison. In females the XX bivalent is indistinguishable from the autosomes. To the meiotic recombination machinery, it is an autosome and has a similar REC landscape. Whereas in spermatocytes the XY bivalent is visually distinct and any MLH1 where not included in the count). (I note if the and Y are paired, which they are at a high rate). The XY pair triggers a response to un-paired chromosomes and only has MLH1 foci within the PAR (the the tips of X and Y). To make a more equivalent comparison I will estimate which bivalent is the XX in oocytes, and subtract that average REC from the category average of each strain.

  1. Compile full-cell data from females (all 20 bivalents measured)
  2. Look at the SC length -ranked data, extract the 3rd longest estimate average REC for this bivalent,
  3. check how variable the REC is across the 1st,2nd,4th, and 5th are.

According to mouse genome website, the X is the 3rd largest chromosome by total amount of DNA (Mb).
